# Coding conventions

## Architecture

- Favor clean, modular architecture with strong separation of concerns.
- Keep modules small and single-purpose; separate business logic from I/O,
  transport, and UI. Extract reusable logic into well-named functions/modules
  instead of duplicating it.
- For Convex, keep query/mutation/action wrappers thin — put real logic in
  plain TypeScript helpers the wrappers call.

## Types: one source of truth

The Convex schema is the source of truth for data shapes — never hand-duplicate
a type that can be derived from it.

- Use the generated types from `convex/_generated/dataModel`: `Id<"table">`
  for document ids and `Doc<"table">` for full documents. Do not re-declare
  these as bare `string`s or hand-written object types.
- Define each validator once (with `v` from `convex/values`) and reuse it
  across the schema and function args; derive its TS type with
  `Infer<typeof theValidator>` rather than re-typing the fields.
- Let types flow from the database through Convex functions to the client
  (end-to-end type safety) instead of re-declaring shapes at each layer.
